  1. Calculate the average log2 foldchange between primary and normal, recurrent and normal, recurrent and primary.
#calculate the mean for each gene per group
normal_mean <- apply(expr.data[,1:5],1, mean)
primary_mean <- apply(expr.data[,6:10],1, mean)
recurrent_mean <- apply(expr.data[,11:15],1, mean)
#calculate the fold change between the groups
## Normal/Primary
foldchange_nor_primary <- normal_mean - primary_mean 
## Normal/Recurrent
foldchange_nor_recurrent <- normal_mean - recurrent_mean
## Primary/Recurrent
foldchange_pri_recurrent <- primary_mean - recurrent_mean
hist(foldchange_nor_primary, 
     xlab = "log2 Fold Change (Normal vs Primary)")

hist(foldchange_nor_recurrent, 
     xlab = "log2 Fold Change (Normal vs Recurrent)")

hist(foldchange_pri_recurrent, 
     xlab = "log2 Fold Change (Primary vs Recurrent)")

#Add log2FC for normal/tumor
expr.data.fc <- expr.data
expr.data.fc$log2FC_nor_pri <- foldchange_nor_primary
expr.data.fc$log2FC_nor_rec <- foldchange_nor_recurrent
expr.data.fc$log2FC_pri_recurrent <- foldchange_pri_recurrent
expr.data.fc <- rownames_to_column(expr.data.fc, var = "gene_ID")
# add Gene_Symbol
library("gage")

  1. Use Gage (unpaired test) to identify differentially UP- and DOWN-regulated gene-sets (using Hallmark and Reactome gene-sets separately). Make the following comparisons: primary vs.Â normal, recurrent vs.Â normal, recurrent vs.Â primary.
#Definition of gage inputs
cn <- colnames(expr.data)
normal <- grep('Normal',cn, ignore.case =T)
primary <- grep('Primary',cn, ignore.case =T)
recurrent <- grep('Recurrent',cn, ignore.case =T)
#Hallmarks
gage_H_pri_no = gage(exprs = expr.data, 
                     gsets = hallmark_list, 
                     set.size=c(10,500), 
                     same.dir = TRUE, 
                     compare ="unpaired", 
                     ref = normal, 
                     samp = primary) 

gage_H_rec_no = gage(exprs = expr.data, 
                     gsets = hallmark_list, 
                     set.size=c(10,500), 
                     same.dir = TRUE, 
                     compare ="unpaired", 
                     ref = normal, 
                     samp = recurrent)

gage_H_pri_rec = gage(exprs = expr.data, 
                      gsets = hallmark_list, 
                      set.size=c(10,500), 
                      same.dir = TRUE, 
                      compare ="unpaired", 
                      ref = primary, 
                      samp = recurrent)
#Reactome database
gage_R_pri_no = gage(exprs = expr.data, 
                     gsets = reactome_entrez, 
                     set.size=c(10,500), 
                     same.dir = TRUE, 
                     compare ="unpaired", 
                     ref = normal, 
                     samp = primary)

Notes

GSEA 1. Detect general trend without setting limit on differential genes 2. Kolmogorov-Smirnov-Test, multiple hypotheses testing correction 3. MSigDB helps finding other related studies

GAGE (Generally Applicable Gene-set Enrichment) [@GAGE] 1. applies to datasets with any number of sample and is based on a parametric gene randomization procedure [@GAGE] 2. Uses log-based fold changes as per gene statistics 3. assumes gene set comes from a different distribution than the background and unses two-sample t-test to account for the gene set specificic variance as well as the background variance 4. adjusts for different experimental designs and sample sizes by decomposing roup-on group comparison into one-on-one comparisons between samples from different groups - derives a global p-value using a meta-test on the p-values from these comparisons for each gene set 5. separates experimentally perturbed gene sets (from literature, single directions) and canonical pathways (from pathway databases, both directions)

Useful links:

  1. Gage http://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/gage.html
  2. msigdbr https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/msigdbr/vignettes/msigdbr-intro.html
  3. single cell RNA seq GSEA https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-020-15298-6

#Data set description

Data retrieved from the TCBA database and includes log2-normalized read counts of RNA-sequencing samples from Glioblastoma multiforme (GBM) patients or healthy control tissues.

Tumor tissues were classified as âPrimaryâ or âRecurrentâ. Control tissues were classified as being âNormal.â.

I used the updated curated gene set collection Hallmark (H) from the MSigDB databse (@Libzerzon et al.2015).
